O. STANDARD TAG VOCABULARY (RECOMMENDED)
==================================================

Goal:
Have a consistent, human-readable tag system for MemCubes so both humans and external tools can filter, group, and search reliably.

Tag format:
- Always "key:value"
- Lowercase keys; values lowercase or snake_case; avoid spaces when possible.

Core keys:
1) project
   - What this belongs to.
   - Examples:
     - "project:startup_alpha"
     - "project:novel_draft_1"
     - "project:pkm_system"
     - "project:social_content_2026"

2) area
   - Domain or functional area.
   - Recommended values:
     - "area:planning"
     - "area:reflection"
     - "area:learning"
     - "area:writing"
     - "area:business"
     - "area:marketing"
     - "area:research"
     - "area:personal"
     - "area:social"

3) priority
   - Perceived importance.
   - Values:
     - "priority:high"
     - "priority:medium"
     - "priority:low"

4) status
   - State in the workflow.
   - Values:
     - "status:idea" (early concept)
     - "status:active" (currently in play)
     - "status:blocked" (waiting on something)
     - "status:done" (completed, but maybe still useful)
     - "status:archived" (no longer relevant, kept for reference)

5) horizon
   - Time horizon.
   - Values:
     - "horizon:today"
     - "horizon:week"
     - "horizon:month"
     - "horizon:quarter"
     - "horizon:year"
     - "horizon:someday"

6) role (optional)
   - Which “hat” the user is wearing.
   - Example values:
     - "role:founder"
     - "role:writer"
     - "role:student"
     - "role:manager"
     - "role:creator"

7) context (optional)
   - Extra useful qualifiers.
   - Example values:
     - "context:experiment"
     - "context:template"
     - "context:reference"
     - "context:meeting_notes"

Usage:
- Each MemCube may have zero or many tags.
- You should normalise tags (e.g., always "priority:high", not "priority:High").
- When generating or loading packs, you can:
  - Filter MemCubes by project, area, priority, etc.
  - Build views grouped by these tags.

